🌿 Punishment, Mercy, and the Cry of a Nation 🌿

The words punishment and lesson are harsh — to hear and to understand.
But what is punishment?
It is the moment when a person comes face to face with the consequences of their own actions.

Nature often forgives our wrongs.
We mock beliefs, we rebel, we boast of self-made power, we turn away from obedience —
and when we do obey, we expect others to obey us.
Yet nature stays silent…
Until the moment comes when the hand of the oppressor rises against the innocent,
when the cry of the powerless pierces the skies,
and when the voice of the oppressed calls upon Divine Justice.
That is when punishment descends.
That is when justice arrives — and justice is merciless.

Punishment is not just about external disasters.
It is when people lose trust, when friendship turns to enmity,
when the heart loses its respect for others,
when wealth overflows but peace vanishes,
when protectors stand but there is no safety,
when evil is celebrated and goodness mocked.

Punishment is not just war or calamity —
it’s when a person feels like a stranger in their own home,
when in the crowd they feel utterly alone,
when every voice turns into noise, and every step leads into emptiness.

Punishment is when the youth turn against their parents,
when parents are blind to their children’s pain.
It is when the preacher’s words become a joke,
when healers stand around while the patient dies.
It is when eyes lose their tears, when hearts freeze,
when people dance as their neighbors burn.

💔 The Pain of Our Times

Karachi — oh Karachi —
what has passed over you, no words can hold.
What happened there was not just violence;
it was a storm, a judgment, a wound so deep
it reopens all old wounds.

When innocent girls fall to the hands of beasts,
when horror echoes through a “civilized” city,
the punishment is not only in what happened —
it’s in what lies behind it,
and in the terrifying question: what might come next?

Are we drunk on our own apathy?
Have we closed our eyes to the rising tides,
to the dangers outside,
to the divisions rotting us from within?

🌍 A Cry to the Divine

O Creator —
are we cut off from Your mercy?
Have we wandered too far?
Are we so deep in our mistakes that we are beyond repair?

But You, O Lord —
if You will, night turns to day,
barren fields bloom again,
hatred melts into love.

If You will, the broken can be made whole,
the lost can be found,
and mercy can pour over those who have forgotten mercy.

O God, open Your gates of mercy upon us.
Save us from ourselves,
from our arrogance, our blindness, our cruelty.
Do not hand us over to each other’s cruelty —
hold us in the embrace of Your grace.

✨ Final Reflection

This is not just about Karachi.
It is about every place, every heart, every nation where people are tearing each other apart.
Where we have stopped caring,
stopped listening,
stopped praying.

Let us pray:
that we awaken, not through tragedy,
but through the miracle of softening hearts.
Let us pray for a world where His mercy outweighs His wrath.

